<TITLE> Expats want honorary citizenship for Prof Seely </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 22 (bdnews24.com) -- More than 70 distinguished expatriate Bangladeshis recently urged the government to award honourary citizenship and Ekushe Padak to professor Clinton Booth Seely for his lifelong devotion and contribution to Bengali language and literature. Clinton B Seely is an emeritus professor of Bengali at the University of Chicago, USA. The expatriate Bangladeshis living in the US, Europe and Australia made the appeal in a joint letter to the prime minister and the cultural affairs minister, a statement issued recently said. Prof Seely worked on Bengali language and literature since 1960s when he was a volunteer science teacher at Barisal Zilla School. In 1971, he actively supported Bangladesh's liberation war. But Bangladesh is yet to accord him any recognition for his contributions though he received a number of awards from West Bengal, including the prestigious Ananda Purashkar. Prof Seely is a renowned American academic, professor of Bengali, and a researcher author and translator. His highly acclaimed literary biography of Bengali poet Jibanananda Das (A Poet Apart: A Literary Biography of the Bengali Poet Jibanananda Das (18991954) is an important work of its kind. He also translated the works of Ramprasad Sen (Grace and Mercy in Her Wild Hairs) and Michael Madhusudan Dutt (The Slaying of Meghanada: A Ramayana from Colonial Bengal - translation of Michael's epic, Meghnadbodh Kavya). Besides, Prof Seely authored numerous scholarly papers, and wrote a number of pedagogical books and software packages for students of Bengali. He has to his credit numerous scholarly papers on Bangla language, literature and culture. For the last two decades, Prof Seely has been one of the key organisers of annual Bango Sanskriti Sammelan in USA, which has been held regularly for nearly four decade
